          "body": "The account of the Good Shepherd's removal of three unnamed shepherds in one month (11:8) is one of the chapter's most debated verses. The three have been identified variously as the three offices of prophet, priest, and king; as specific historical figures in the Seleucid or Maccabean period; and as representatives of the leadership classes who collectively opposed the true Shepherd. The identification matters less than the theological dynamic: the Good Shepherd confronts and removes bad leadership, and the flock resents it. The text names mutual loathing — *my soul was impatient with them, and their soul also was weary of me* (11:8). This is the turning point. The shepherd does not abandon the flock arbitrarily; he withdraws because the relationship has become one of active contempt on both sides. The withdrawal announcement of verse 9 — *I will not pasture you* — is not cold indifference but the inevitable consequence of rejected care. The image of the remaining flock eating one another's flesh (11:9) is both metaphor and historical reality: in 70 AD, Josephus records that the siege of Jerusalem devolved into precisely this kind of internecine horror among the city's factions."
