        "excerpt": "Thus says the Lord my God, 'Pasture the flock doomed to slaughter.'",
        "body": "The commission of 11:4 is one of the most theologically saturated sentences in Zechariah. YHWH commands His prophet to shepherd a flock already marked for death, already being exploited by both buyers and sellers who profit from its destruction without conscience (11:5). The three groups named in verse 5 — buyers, sellers, and the flock's own shepherds — are each implicated in different ways: buyers kill without guilt, sellers invoke divine blessing over their profits, and shepherds feel no pity. The situation is not that the flock lacks shepherds; it is that every available shepherd has become predatory. Into this, YHWH sends the Good Shepherd.\n\nThe two staffs named in 11:7 are not decorative; they are the chapter's covenant architecture. *Noam* (Favor, pleasantness) represents the external canopy of providential protection YHWH maintained over Israel among the nations — a restraining influence on Israel's enemies analogous to what Paul calls the *katechon* (the restrainer) in 2 Thessalonians 2:6-7. *Chevel* (Union, cord) represents the internal bond of the covenant community — the fragile but real solidarity between Judah and Israel that the prophets consistently named as the sign of covenant health (Ezekiel 37:15-22; Isaiah 11:13). To pastor with both staffs is to offer complete protection.\n\nThe three shepherds removed in one month (11:8) represent the leadership obstruction the Good Shepherd encounters. The identity of the three has occupied commentators from ancient times: the Targum identifies them as Moses, Aaron, and Miriam; patristic writers suggest prophet, priest, and king; modern critical scholars propose specific Hasmonean or Seleucid-era rulers. The uncertainty itself is instructive — the three function as representative of all false leadership structures that the Good Shepherd must clear away before genuine care can be offered. Their removal is swift (one month), comprehensive (three leaders), and mutual — *my soul was impatient with them, and their soul also was weary of me* (11:8).\n\nThe withdrawal announcement of 11:9 is the chapter's pastoral and theological crisis. When YHWH says 'I will not pasture you,' He is not abandoning the flock arbitrarily — He is responding to a relationship that has become one of active mutual contempt. The language of divine *nephesh* (soul/self) growing impatient echoes Numbers 21:4 and Judges 10:16, where the same Hebrew expression describes the profound relational strain in the divine-human bond. The image of the remaining flock devouring one another's flesh (11:9) became grotesquely literal in the Roman siege of 70 AD, when Josephus (*Jewish War* 5-6) recorded the factional cannibalism among Jerusalem's defenders.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Haregah* (slaughter, 11:4, 7) — the same root as in Psalm 44:22 (*'for your sake we are killed all the day long'*) quoted by Paul in Romans 8:36. *Noam* (Favor) — appears elsewhere only in Psalm 27:4 as the 'beauty of the LORD' and in Psalm 90:17 as the 'favor of the Lord our God.' *Nephesh* (soul, 11:8) — the whole self, the seat of will and emotion; to say YHWH's *nephesh* was impatient is to speak of the full divine being's grieved response to the broken relationship."
